[[File:Atlantic Coastal Plain.svg|thumb|right|300px|The Atlantic coastal plain covers parts of [[Massachusetts]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[New Jersey]], [[Delaware]], [[Maryland]], the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]], [[Virginia]], [[North Carolina]], [[South Carolina]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], and [[Florida]] ([[Alabama]] is part of the [[Gulf Coastal Plain]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=Generalized Landscape Regions of New York State|url=http://www.p12.nysed.gov/assessment/reftable/earthscience-rt/esrt2011-engr.pdf|work=Earth Science Reference Tables|publisher=NYSED|accessdate=12 November 2012}}</ref> ]] [[File:Harvested Wheat 1 (3727629107).jpg|thumb|right|Wheat field near [[Centreville, Maryland|Centreville]] on the [[Eastern Shore of Maryland]], with flat terrain typical of the Atlantic coastal plain]] {{Main|Atlantic Plain}}
The '''Atlantic coastal plain''' is a [[United States physiographic region|physiographic region]] of low relief along the [[East Coast of the United States]]. It extends {{convert|2200|mi|km}} from the [[New York Bight]]<ref>{{cite web |last= Stoffer |first=Phil |author2=Messina, Paula |title = The Atlantic Coastal Plain | url = http://www.geo.hunter.cuny.edu/bight/coastal.html | work = Geology and Geography of New York Bight Beaches }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blm.gov/wildlife/pl_03sum.htm |title=South Atlantic Coastal Plain |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090424093048/http://www.blm.gov/wildlife/pl_03sum.htm |archivedate=2009-04-24 |df= }}</ref> southward to a Georgia/Florida section of the [[Eastern Continental Divide]], which demarcates the plain from the [[ACF River Basin]] in the [[Gulf Coastal Plain]] to the west. The province is bordered on the west by the [[Atlantic Seaboard fall line]] and the [[Piedmont (United States)|Piedmont plateau]], to the east by the [[Atlantic Ocean]], and to the south by the [[United States physiographic region|Floridian province]]. The [[Outer Lands]] archipelagic region forms the insular northeasternmost extension of the Atlantic [[coastal plain]].
The province's average elevation is less than 900 meters above sea level and extends some 50 to 100 kilometers inland from the ocean.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} The coastal plain is normally wet, including many rivers, [[marsh]], and [[swampland]].{{Citation needed|reason=This seems unbelievable since most of the land is farmable.|date=December 2008}} There are no [[hill]]s or [[mountain]]s in this region of North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.study.com/academy/lesson/atlantic-coastal-plain-lesson-for-kids.html|title=Atlantic Coastal Plain Lesson for Kids - Study.com|publisher=}}</ref> It is composed primarily of [[sedimentary rock]] and [[diagenesis|unlithified]] [[sediment]]s and is primarily used for [[agriculture]].<ref>[http://ddr.nal.usda.gov/bitstream/10113/18162/1/IND20441752.pdf Water table management in the eastern coastal plain] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721072047/http://ddr.nal.usda.gov/bitstream/10113/18162/1/IND20441752.pdf |date=July 21, 2011 }}</ref> The area is subdivided into the [[United States physiographic region|Embayed and Sea Island physiographic provinces]], as well as the [[Mid-Atlantic states|Mid-Atlantic]] and [[South Atlantic States|South Atlantic]] coastal plains.
