{{short description|Region comprising the Scandinavian Peninsula, Finland, Karelia, and the Kola Peninsula}} __NOTOC__ {{for|the Fennoscandian Shield|Baltic Shield}} {{Infobox peninsulas |name = Fennoscandia |local_name = |image_name = Scandinavia M2002074 lrg.jpg |image_caption = Fennoscandia in March 2002 |image_alt = |map_image = Fennoscandia.png |map_size = |map_caption = Map highlighting the Fennoscandian, Scandinavian and the Kola Peninsulas |location = [[Northern Europe]] |waterbody = [[Arctic Sea]], [[Atlantic Ocean]] |coordinates = {{coord|63.0000|N|17.0000|E|source:wikidata|display=inline,title}} |area_km2 = |highest_mount = [[Galdhøpiggen]] |elevation_m = 2,469 |country = [[Norway]] |country_admin_divisions_title = |country_admin_divisions = Mainland |country1 = [[Sweden]] |country1_admin_divisions_title = |country1_admin_divisions = Mainland |country2 = [[Finland]] |country2_admin_divisions_title = |country2_admin_divisions = Mainland |country3 = [[Russia]] |country3_admin_divisions_title = |country3_admin_divisions = Whole or part of the mainland area of [[Murmansk Oblast]], [[Republic of Karelia]], and [[Leningrad Oblast]] |demonym = |population = |population_as_of = |density_km2 = |ethnic_groups= |additional_info= }} '''Fennoscandia''' ({{lang-fi|Fennoskandia}}; {{lang-sv|Fennoskandien}}; {{lang-no|Fennoskandia}}; {{lang-ru|Фенноскандия Fennoskandiya}}) or the '''Fennoscandian Peninsula''' is the geographical [[peninsula]] comprising the [[Scandinavian Peninsula]], [[Finland]], [[Karelia]], and the [[Kola Peninsula]].<ref>''The Oxford Handbook of the Archaeology and Anthropology of Hunter-Gatherers'', eds. Vicki Cummings; Peter Jordan; Marek Zvelebil (Oxfored; New York: Oxford University Press, 2014), p. 838</ref> It encompasses [[Finland]], [[Norway]] and [[Sweden]],<ref>Sten Lavsund; Tuire Nygren; Erling Solberg (2003). [http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-140524869.html "Status of moose populations and challenges to moose management in Fennoscandia"]. Alces. 2003. HighBeam Research.</ref> as well as [[Murmansk Oblast]], much of the [[Republic of Karelia]], and parts of northern [[Leningrad Oblast]] in [[Russia]]. Its name comes from the Latin words ''Fennia'' (Finland) and ''Scandia'' (Scandinavian).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yourdictionary.com/fennoscandia |title=Fennoscandia [fen′ō skan′dē ə] |author= |date= |website=Your Dictionary |publisher=LoveToKnow, Corp. |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref> The term was first used by the Finnish geologist [[Wilhelm Ramsay]] in 1898.<ref>{{cite journal |last=De Geer |first=Sten |author-link=Sten De Geer |year=1928 |title=Das geologische Fennoskandia und das geographische Baltoskandia |url=https://dspace.ut.ee/bitstream/handle/10062/15327/geologische_de_geer_ocr.pdf?sequence=5&isAllowed=y |accessdate=22 April 2018 |journal=[[Geografiska Annaler]] |publisher=Swedish Society for Anthropology and Geography |volume=10 |issue= |pages=119–139 |oclc=604361828 |language=German}}</ref> Geologically, the area is distinct because its [[bedrock]] is [[Archean]] [[granite]] and [[gneiss]] with very little [[limestone]], in contrast to adjacent areas in Europe.
The similar term '''Fenno-Scandinavia''' typically refers to a cultural or political grouping of Finland with [[Scandinavia]] (Denmark, Sweden, and Norway),<ref>''Bulletin - Canadian Library Association'', Volume 20. Canadian Library Association., 1963. p. 179.</ref> which is a subset of the [[Nordic countries]].
