{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2011}} '''Julian Wolpert''' (born 1932) is Bryant Professor Emeritus of Geography, Public Affairs, and Urban Planning at [[Princeton University]]'s [[Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs|Woodrow Wilson School]], where he taught from 1973-2005<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.utrc2.org/directory/people.php?viewid=54 |title=Directory: People: Dr. Julian Wolpert |publisher=UTRC2.org |date=September 10, 2007 |accessdate=December 23, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426070204/http://www.utrc2.org/directory/people.php?viewid=54 |archivedate=April 26, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and chaired the Program in Urban and Regional Planning. He was previously a member of the Regional Science Department at the University of Pennsylvania (1963–73). He is a graduate of Columbia University (BA) and the [[University of Wisconsin-Madison|University of Wisconsin-Madison, MS]] & PhD (Geography).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wws.princeton.edu/people/display_person.xml?netid=jwolpert&display=professors |title=Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs &#124; Display Person |publisher=Wws.princeton.edu |date= |accessdate=December 23, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230090929/http://wws.princeton.edu/people/display_person.xml?netid=jwolpert&display=Professors |archivedate=December 30, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He served as a U.S .Navy officer from 1956 to 1959. He was elected to the National Academy of Sciences and AAAS. He has been a fellow at the [[Russell Sage Foundation]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.russellsage.org/visiting-scholars/julian-wolpert |title=Julian Wolpert &#124; Russell Sage Foundation |publisher=Russellsage.org |date= |accessdate=December 23, 2011}}</ref> the Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral and Social Sciences, and the Woodrow Wilson Center and has been a [[Guggenheim fellow]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gf.org/fellows/16031-julian-wolpert |title=Julian Wolpert - John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation |publisher=Gf.org |date= |accessdate=December 23, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527024849/http://www.gf.org/fellows/16031-julian-wolpert |archivedate=May 27, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Wolpert is a nationally cited scholar in the fields of [[charity (practice)|location theory, urban development, migration, public and social services, and the analysis of charity]], [[philanthropy|philanthropy, and the nonprofit sector]], and has testified before Congress about the regulation of philanthropy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-12-24/opinion/op-17814_1_los-angeles |title=Julian Wolpert &#124; LOS ANGELES TIMES INTERVIEW : Julian Wolpert : Charity in Los Angeles- or the Lack Thereof - Los Angeles Times |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=December 24, 1995 |accessdate=December 23, 2011}}</ref> He has challenged [[conservatives]] who advocate for charitable rather than public service approaches to social policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huppi.com/kangaroo/L-welfarecharity.htm |title=Welfare can be replaced by charity |publisher=Huppi.com |date= |accessdate=December 23, 2011}}</ref> Wolpert served as Vice President, then President of the Association of American Geographers and Vice President of the Regional Science Association and the American Geographical Society and was elected to the American Institute of Certified Planners.
Wolpert's earliest research focused on testing social and economic theory based upon spatial data, productivity gaps elated to environmental risk and imperfect information, the migration decision, the relation between commuting and migration, siting and closing amenity and "nimby" facilities, and disaster evacuation, and the effects of sprawl on regional development. More recently, his studies concerned the nonprofit marketplace in cities, nonprofit service representation and saturation of neighborhoods, locational variations in generosity, distributional effects of foundations, the fiscal viability of nonprofits, and methods for planning and evaluating nonprofit organizations and foundations.
