{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}
[[File:HolbyBlue DVD cover.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The cover of the DVD for the first series of ''HolbyBlue''|alt=The ''HolbyBlue'' logo above five characters.]]
''[[HolbyBlue]]'' is a British [[police procedural]] [[drama]] which was created by [[Tony Jordan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4950314.stm|title=Police spin-off planned for Holby|date=27 April 2006|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref> The show is set in the fictional city of [[Holby]], and focuses on the daily lives of police officers working at Holby South police station. The show's [[ensemble cast]] for series one consisted of [[Jimmy Akingbola]], [[Joe Jacobs (actor)|Joe Jacobs]], [[David Sterne]], [[Cal MacAninch]], [[James Hillier (actor)|James Hillier]], [[Kacey Ainsworth]], [[Richard Harrington (actor)|Richard Harrington]], [[Zöe Lucker]], [[Chloe Howman]], [[Kieran O'Brien]], [[Tim Pigott-Smith]] and [[Elaine Glover]].<ref name="Cast">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbyblue/characters_actors.shtml|title=Characters & Actors|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref> Pigott-Smith departed the drama in the final episode of the first series at the conclusion of his character's storyline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbyblue/series1_episode8.shtml|title=Series 1, Episode 8|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref> Actors [[Oliver Milburn]] and [[James Thornton (actor)|James Thornton]] joined the drama for series two.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/holby-blue/news/a77926/oliver-milburn-joins-cast-of-holby-blue/|title=Oliver Milburn joins cast of 'Holby Blue'|last=Hilton|first=Beth|date=17 October 2007|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2008/01/11/james-to-join-holbyblue-497211/|title=James to join HolbyBlue|date=11 January 2008|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|publisher=[[DMG Media]]|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>

The creation of ''HolbyBlue'' was announced on 27 April 2006 by the [[BBC]]. It was revealed that the show would have links to British medical drama ''[[Holby City]]''. Tony Jordan was recruited to write scripts for the show and work out "how storylines between the police station and the hospital could be intertwined."<ref name="BBC create">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4950314.stm|title=Police spin-off planned for Holby|date=27 April 2006|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref> The first series began filming at the end of January 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/holby-blue/news/a42293/filming-begins-on-holbyblue/|title=Filming begins on 'HolbyBlue'|last=Green|first=Kris|date=31 January 2007|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref> commenced airing on 8 May 2007 at 8{{nbsp}}pm, one week later than scheduled for unknown reasons,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/holby-blue/news/a45336/holbyblue-pushed-back-a-week/|title='HolbyBlue' pushed back a week|last=Green|first=Kris|date=17 April 2007|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref> and concluded on 26 June 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbyblue/series1episodeguide.shtml|title=Series 1 Episode Guide|work=[[BBC One]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref> On 21 June 2007, it was announced that ''HolbyBlue'' would air a second series in 2008, this time for an extended run of twelve episodes.<ref name="S2 12">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/holby-blue/news/a62221/holbyblue-picked-up-for-extended-second-run/|title='HolbyBlue' picked up for extended second run|last=Green|first=Kris|date=21 June 2007|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref> Filming recommenced in late 2007 in [[Surrey]],<ref name="S2 12"/> and the second series began airing on 20 March 2008, concluding on 5 June 2008.<ref name="Ep Guide">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/holbyblue/episodeguide.shtml|title=Episode Guide|work=[[BBC One]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref> Two series of ''HolbyBlue'' aired in total.<ref name="Ep Guide"/>

On 6 August 2008, the BBC revealed that ''HolbyBlue'' would not be recommissioned for a third series, due to a decline in viewership. The second series started with 5.6 million viewers, but by the end of May had fallen to 2.5 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7545311.stm|title=BBC axes police drama Holby Blue|date=6 August 2008|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref> Upon the cancellation of the show, Red Planet Picture's drama executive Claire Phillips stated that "''HolbyBlue'' set new standards for 8{{nbsp}}pm dramas, in terms of production values, storytelling and casting."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/aug/06/bbc.television|title=BBC pulls the plug on Holby Blue|last=Conlan|first=Tara|date=6 August 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref> At the 2007 and 2008 [[Inside Soap Awards]], ''HolbyBlue'' was nominated under the Best Drama category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2007/07/03/inside-soap-tv-award-nominations-in-full-3429693/|title=Inside Soap TV award nominations in full|last=Kevan|first=Paul|date=3 July 2007|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|publisher=[[DMG Media]]|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.talkbackthames.tv/?s=news&b=29&abc=710|title=The Bill triumphs at Inside Soap Awards|date=30 September 2008|work=[[Talkback Thames]]|publisher=[[Bertelsmann]]|accessdate=1 January 2018|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927145222/http://www.talkbackthames.tv/?s=news&b=29&abc=710|archivedate=27 September 2011}}</ref> Ainsworth and Lucker both received nominations for Best Actress at the [[TV Choice Awards|TV Quick & TV Choice Awards]] in 2007, while ''HolbyBlue'' was nominated under the Best New Drama Series category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvquick.co.uk/|title=Welcome to the TVQuick & TVChoice Awards 2007!|work=[[TV Quick]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group|Bauer]]|accessdate=1 January 2018|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070603021142/http://www.tvquick.co.uk/|archivedate=3 June 2007}}</ref> Akingbola was put forward for Best Male Performance in TV at the 2008 [[Screen Nation Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hamiltonhodell.co.uk/talent/jimmy-akingbola/|title=Jimmy Akingbola|publisher=hamiltonhodell.com|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref>

